VALUES
(43, 10, 5, 20, 19, 27, 27, 'the voice of strangers', 'Understanding Voices and Instruction', 'This connection highlights the importance of discernment in recognizing true guidance versus misleading instruction. Both passages emphasize the need to avoid following voices or teachings that lead one away from knowledge and truth.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 5, 41, 4, 24, 24, 'voice of strangers', 'Understanding Voices and Hearing', 'This connection highlights the importance of discernment in hearing. Both passages emphasize the need to recognize true voices and the consequences of what one chooses to hear.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 5, 49, 4, 11, 15, 'voice of strangers', 'Understanding the Voice of Christ', 'This connection highlights the importance of recognizing true guidance and avoiding deception. Both passages emphasize the need for discernment in following Christ and not being led astray by false teachings.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 5, 66, 2, 2, 2, 'not follow, but will flee from him', 'Recognition of True Voices', 'This connection highlights the discernment of true from false voices. Both passages emphasize the importance of recognizing and rejecting those who are not genuine, as seen in the ''stranger'' and the ''liars.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 5, 11, 22, 7, 7, 'stranger will they not follow', 'Recognition of True Voices', 'This connection highlights the discernment of true voices versus strangers. In John 10:5, the followers flee from strangers, paralleling Jehoshaphat''s desire to seek a true prophet of the Lord in 1 Kings 22:7.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 6, 23, 56, 11, 11, 'they understood not what things they were', 'Understanding of Shepherds', 'This connection highlights the theme of misunderstanding among shepherds. Both passages emphasize the inability to comprehend their roles, with Jesus noting that they ''understood not'' and Isaiah describing ''shepherds that cannot understand.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 6, 19, 82, 5, 5, 'understood not what things they were', 'Understanding and Darkness Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of lack of understanding in both passages. In John 10:6, Jesus'' audience does not comprehend his message, paralleling Psalms 82:5, where people walk in darkness and do not understand.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 6, 20, 28, 5, 5, 'understood not what things they were', 'Understanding and Judgment', 'This connection highlights the theme of understanding in both passages. John 10:6 notes that the listeners did not understand Jesus'' words, while Proverbs 28:5 states that those who seek the Lord gain understanding, contrasting the lack of understanding among evil men.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 6, 19, 106, 7, 7, 'understood not', 'Understanding and Memory', 'This connection highlights the theme of misunderstanding and lack of remembrance. Both passages emphasize the failure to comprehend significant events, whether Jesus'' teachings or God''s wonders in Egypt.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 6, 23, 6, 9, 10, 'understood not what things they were', 'Understanding and Perception', 'This connection highlights the theme of misunderstanding in both passages. In John 10:6, Jesus notes that the people did not understand his parable, paralleling Isaiah 6:9-10, where the people are told they hear but do not perceive.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 6, 27, 12, 10, 10, 'understood not what things they were', 'Understanding and Wisdom Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of understanding in both passages. John 10:6 notes that the listeners did not understand Jesus'' words, while Daniel 12:10 states that the wicked will not understand, but the wise will. Both emphasize a distinction between those who grasp spiritual truths and those who do not.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 6, 40, 13, 13, 14, 'understood not what things they were', 'Understanding Through Parables', 'Both passages emphasize a lack of understanding among the listeners. In John, Jesus notes they ''understood not,'' while Matthew highlights that they ''hear not, neither do they understand.'' This connection highlights the theme of spiritual blindness in parabolic teaching.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 7, 43, 14, 6, 6, 'the door of the sheep', 'Jesus as the Path to Salvation', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' role as the means to access spiritual safety and truth. Both passages emphasize that Jesus is essential for approaching God, with ''the door'' and ''the way'' symbolizing pathways to salvation.', 'theme', 0.475, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 7, 49, 2, 18, 18, 'I am the door of the sheep', 'Access Through Christ', 'This connection highlights the theme of access to God. In John 10:7, Jesus identifies himself as the door, implying that he provides a way for the sheep to enter. Ephesians 2:18 emphasizes that through him, believers have access to the Father, reinforcing the idea of Jesus as the means of connection.', 'theme', 0.45399999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 7, 43, 10, 1, 1, 'I am the door of the sheep', 'Connection of the Door Metaphor', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of the ''door'' as essential for entering the sheepfold. Jesus identifies Himself as the door, contrasting legitimate access with those who attempt to enter unlawfully.', 'theme', 0.43999999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 7, 26, 34, 31, 31, NULL, 'Connection of Shepherd and Flock', 'This connection highlights the relationship between God and His people. In both passages, the imagery of a flock and a shepherd is present, emphasizing care and guidance.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 7, 19, 79, 13, 13, NULL, 'Shepherd and Sheep Imagery', 'This connection highlights the imagery of sheep in both passages. Jesus identifies Himself as the ''door of the sheep,'' while Psalms refers to the people as ''sheep of thy pasture,'' emphasizing the relationship between the shepherd and the sheep.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 7, 19, 100, 3, 3, 'sheep', 'Connection of Sheep Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship between God and His people, depicted as sheep. Jesus identifies Himself as the door for the sheep, while Psalms acknowledges that we are the sheep of His pasture.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 7, 58, 10, 19, 22, 'I am the door of the sheep', 'Access to God through Christ', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus as the means of access to God. In John 10:7, Jesus identifies himself as ''the door,'' while Hebrews 10:19-22 speaks of entering ''into the holiest'' through his sacrifice, emphasizing the new way he provides for believers.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 8, 26, 34, 2, 2, 'thieves and robbers', 'Shepherds and Thieves Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the role of shepherds and their failure to care for the flock. John refers to those before him as ''thieves and robbers,'' while Ezekiel condemns the shepherds of Israel for feeding themselves instead of the flocks.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 8, 24, 23, 1, 1, 'thieves and robbers', 'Shepherds and False Leaders', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of false leaders who harm the sheep. John refers to them as ''thieves and robbers,'' while Jeremiah warns against ''pastors that destroy and scatter the sheep.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 8, 43, 10, 1, 1, 'thieves and robbers', 'Thieves and Robbers Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''thieves and robbers'' as those who do not enter the sheepfold properly. This connection highlights the contrast between true shepherds and false ones.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 8, 23, 56, 10, 12, 'thieves and robbers', 'Shepherds and Thieves Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the failure of leaders to guide the people. John refers to those before him as ''thieves and robbers,'' while Isaiah describes ''greedy dogs'' and ''shepherds that cannot understand.'' This connection highlights the theme of false leadership.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 8, 26, 22, 25, 28, 'thieves and robbers', 'False Leaders and Deception', 'This connection highlights the theme of false leaders who deceive and exploit the vulnerable. Both passages describe individuals who act as thieves and robbers, leading the people astray and causing harm.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 8, 43, 10, 27, 27, 'the sheep did not hear them', 'Connection of Sheep and Voice', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship between the shepherd and the sheep. The first verse mentions that the sheep did not hear thieves, while the second states that the sheep hear the shepherd''s voice.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 8, 44, 5, 36, 36, 'thieves and robbers', 'False Leaders and Their Followers', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of false leaders who lead people astray. In John 10:8, these leaders are described as ''thieves and robbers,'' while Acts 5:36 recounts a leader whose followers were ''scattered'' after his death, illustrating the futility of following such figures.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 9, 43, 14, 6, 6, 'he shall be saved', 'Connection of Access to Salvation', 'Both passages emphasize that Jesus is essential for salvation. In John 10:9, He is described as ''the door'' through which one enters to be saved, while in John 14:6, He identifies Himself as ''the way'' to the Father.', 'theme', 0.7549999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 9, 49, 2, 18, 18, 'shall be saved', 'Access and Salvation Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of access to salvation. In John 10:9, entering through the door leads to salvation, while Ephesians 2:18 emphasizes access to the Father through the Spirit.', 'theme', 0.6639999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 9, 43, 10, 7, 7, 'I am the door', 'Connection of Jesus as Door', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' role as ''the door.'' This connection highlights the idea of access to salvation and safety for the sheep.', 'theme', 0.58, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 9, 45, 5, 1, 2, 'he shall be saved', 'Access and Salvation Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of access to salvation. In John 10:9, entering through the door leads to being saved, while Romans 5:1-2 emphasizes access to grace through faith, which results in peace with God.', 'theme', 0.5309999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
